<TEXT>
in this neat prosperous market town 
in middle england a farm workers wife says shell never vote for 
margaret thatcher again 
she simply doesnt know whats happening to people said 
30yearold joanne woodward a bystander interrupted her the 
womans a tyrant 
for the prime ministers conservative party candidate charles 
prior it is tough on the campaign trail in midstaffordshire the 
socialist labor party looks set to capture the once unshakeable 
conservative constituency in todays byelection 
byelections which fill vacant parliamentary seats are always 
watched for indications of the standing of the government this one 
threatens the tories with their worst byelection defeat in 50 
years 
midstaffordshires last member of parliament who committed 
suicide in december held the district with a huge majority in 
britains 1987 general election now local opinion polls show labor 
up to 28 points ahead 
the labor party poses its most serious challenge since mrs 
thatcher won power in may 1979 and victory here would bolster 
labors prospects of winning the next general election 
those elections arent due until 1992 
i wont deny it we are in some difficulty said prior a 
43yearold publisher 
a brooding statue of lichfields most famous son the 
18thcentury poet and dictionary compiler samuel johnson dominates 
the market place of a town that as far as anyone can remember has 
never voted socialist 
lichfield with 24000 people is the affluent end of a 
semirural constituency north of birmingham 
the people are mostly skilled bluecollar workers and young 
homeowning couples people who through the 1980s deserted labor for 
a slice of the prosperity brought by mrs thatchers freemarket 
revolution 
now they are hard hit by interest rates soaring to 15 percent 
and inflation at 77 percent and rising both have roughly doubled 
since 1987 when mrs thatcher won her unprecedented third straight 
election 
on top of that lichfield votes amid a national furor over the 
introduction next month of a new property tax that will cost many 
families up to onethird more 
there are just two topics in the political small talk over the 
handshakes the tax and mrs thatcher 
she had a lot of good ideas in the beginning and ive always 
voted conservative said mrs woodward but now shes making a 
real mess of things theyd do much better with a different 
leader 
mrs woodward lives in a rentfree cottage on the farm where her 
husband manages the piggery the woodwards paid no property taxes 
in the past but now they must each pay 560 under the new tax 
system 
labors candidate sylvia heal a 47yearold social worker is 
also benefitting from the collapse of the political center after 
the 1987 general election 
the centrist social and liberal democrats tim jones a local 
lawyer took 23 percent of the midstaffordshire vote last time 
compared with labors 25 percent and the tories 50 percent 
jones is down to around 9 percent in the polls with the 
conservatives prior battling for 2830 percent and mrs heal at 
more than 50 percent 
pranksters and singleissue candidates are also expected to grab 
some of the vote 
nine fringe candidates are counting on the ultraprotest vote 
they include lindy sinclairlove of the nice party whose platform 
is taxexempt status for prostitutes 
they probably wont get more than a few dozen votes apiece but 
thats not the point their efforts are worthwhile just for the 
pleasure of watching a tv newscaster bound by equal coverage laws 
trying to keep a straight face as he reads out screaming lord 
sutch monster raving loony party 
</TEXT>
