the human race is 
accelerating the global warming trend by cutting down the worlds 
forests too fast the executive director of the un environment 
program says 
on a global basis only one tree is replanted for every 10 that 
are cut the official mostafa tolba said wednesday 
the deforestation is contributing to the greenhouse effect the 
greatest environmental threat facing humanity he told a conference 
on business and the environment 
he called for a major effort to restore forests around the world 
and to cut emissions of carbon dioxide a heattrapping gas that is 
building up in the atmosphere 
controls on carbon dioxide are inevitable he said calling 
on industry to conduct massive research into production methods 
that pollute less 
tolba a microbiologist from egypt played a major role in 
negotiating the 1987 montreal protocol to reduce use of chemicals 
that deplete the ozone layer the goal is to establish an 
international agreement on greenhouse gases by 1992 
carbon dioxide the main greenhouse effect gas is produced by 
the burning of fossil fuels like oil gas and coal deforestation 
also contributes to the problem because living trees absorb carbon 
dioxide 
the globe 90 conference which began sunday and ends friday 
has attracted more than 2200 delegates from 56 countries an 
accompanying trade fair has drawn more than 600 exhibitors from 15 
countries 
about 200 indians on wednesday staged a demonstration in 
vancouver to protest pollution and the lack of indian 
representation at the conference 
saul terry president of the union of british columbia indians 
chiefs said natives want a say in forming the kinds of policies 
that will affect the environment 
