<TEXT>
a former navy procurement official and two 
consultants are under indictment on charges they conspired to pass 
confidential contract information to defense firms 
george g stone a former division head at the navys space and 
naval warfare systems command is accused of participating in the 
conspiracy with consultants thomas e muldoon and mark c saunders 
the indictment returned wednesday by a federal grand jury in 
alexandria va is the latest product of an investigation of 
pentagon procurement fraud nicknamed operation ill wind 
it charged that muldoon relayed data that saunders had obtained 
from stone to a division of litton industries inc and to norden 
systems a subsidiary of united technologies corp 
muldoon gave saunders 32000 of the 96000 he was paid by 
litton and 13750 of the 27500 that he received from norden the 
indictment said 
stone is charged with using his influence to help norden stay in 
the competition for the lucrative contract 
the indictment did not charge stone with receiving any of the 
money that muldoon was paid but it suggested he was paid for 
keeping norden in the running 
the indictment recounted a wiretapped conversation during which 
stone allegedly told saunders that norden made the cut to be 
one of the final four competitors for the contract 
stone was quoted as saying that keeping norden in the 
competition was not a waste of time if it puts you know bread 
on the table 
the indictment quoted stone as saying his efforts had been a 
piece of cake and that he and saunders were due 
muldoon convicted last december of bribing another pentagon 
procurement official is also accused of trying to peddle the 
information to ltv corp and grumman corp which were also 
competing for the contract to build a battlefield air traffic 
control system 
the three defendants also are accused of conspiring to pass 
information about a separate contract to unisys corp 
three former norden executives have pleaded guilty to 
participating in the scheme to pay muldoon for the inside 
information on the contract selection process 
no charges have been brought against litton or any of its 
employees 
the three defendants were each charged with conspiracy wire 
fraud and conversion of government property the charges against 
each of the three carry a maximum sentence upon conviction of 45 
years in prison 
muldoon was sentenced in february to 27 months in prison for his 
december bribery conviction 
