<TEXT>
scientists said today that a key natural process 
could not have produced the global warming of the past 100 years by 
itself supporting the idea that the greenhouse effect is already 
raising global temperatures 
only about threefifths of that warming could have come from a 
natural longterm influence of the oceans the researchers 
computer simulation suggests 
the result is presented in todays issue of the british journal 
nature by tml wigley and scb raper of the university of east 
anglia in norwich england 
they said the result does not prove that greenhouse warming has 
begun other scientists agreed but split on how strongly the 
result bolsters the idea 
the greenhouse effect refers to a warming caused by a buildup in 
the atmosphere of certain gases such as carbon dioxide chiefly 
from human activity scientists are concerned that it could 
eventually alter climates and rainfall patterns and lead to coastal 
flooding from raised ocean levels 
but they disagree on whether the greenhouse effect has yet 
produced any detectable impact 
the earth has warmed by about ninetenths of a degree fahrenheit 
over the past 100 years 
a major problem in demonstrating a role for the greenhouse 
effect is that scientists do not know how much of the warming comes 
from longterm natural variability said gerald meehl of the 
national center for atmospheric research in boulder colo 
the oceans which slowly absorb and release huge amounts of 
heat are probably the most likely source of this longterm 
influence he said 
the simulation reported in the nature paper found that over 
intervals of up to 100 years the oceans might produce a trend of 
up to about half a degree fahrenheit 
that means the ocean influence could not have produced the 
observed global warming by itself the researchers wrote yet we 
still cannot claim to have unequivocally detected the greenhouse 
effect they said 
researcher robert cess said the study cannot rule out the idea 
that the oceans did produce the global warming the simulation was 
too simplified to produce a firm conclusion said cess an 
atmospheric sciences professor at the state university of new york 
at stony brook 
but researcher stephen schneider of the atmospheric research 
center who called himself 80 percent certain that greenhouse 
warming has begun said the result adds to his belief 
its not proof yet he said but its another step along 
the way 
scientists will need another 10 years to 20 years of 
observations to be sure if they are seeing a greenhouse warming he 
said 
</TEXT>
