<TEXT>
soviet azerbaijanis poured across a 
bridge into iran after the soviet union opened a frontier crossing 
for the first time in 73 years irans official tehran radio 
reported 
the people who crossed the araks river bridge wednesday were 
irans first officially sanctioned visitors from the soviet 
republic under an agreement reached after violent demonstrations in 
january over opening the border 
the gates on the bridge swung open to mark the iranian moslem 
new year of 1369 which started wednesday the radio said 
relatives from iran and the soviet azerbaijani region of 
nakhichevan met at the crossing in the city of jolfa said the 
report monitored in cyprus 
many of the people were ecstatic with joy and warmly embraced 
their relatives tehran radio said it gave no figures for the 
number of those crossing 
the iranians showered the arriving soviet moslems with gifts 
including flowers sweets and beverages as well as the koran the 
moslem holy book 
the radio said that an agreement between tehran and moscow 
allowed for all residents living within 2 miles of the border to 
cross unimpeded 
nakhichevan is a mostly moslem enclave surrounded by soviet 
armenia but governed by mainly moslem azerbaijan 
the border between iran and the soviet union was shaken by 
violence starting in december when moslems protesting its closure 
tore down fences and burned border posts 
the tehran radio report indicated the bridge gates had been 
closed since the 1917 russian revolution although the red army did 
not assert complete control over azerbaijan until 1920 
last month the soviet union and iran signed an agreement to 
allow citizens from either side to cross four times a year and 
travel in designated territories for up to 15 days 
the estimated 20 million azerbaijanis in the soviet union and 
iran mostly shiite moslems share the same religion language and 
culture 
