a west german businessman was charged 
today with helping to build a plant in libya that was suspected of 
producing chemical weapons before it was damaged in a fire earlier 
this month 
the indictment against juergen hippenstielimhausen former head 
of the imhausenchemie chemical company charged him with violating 
west germanys export laws and tax evasion 
also today a west german official said libya cut off trade with 
west germany after accusing it of setting fire to the chemical 
plant 
west germany made a formal protest today to the tripoli 
government said the official who spoke on condition of anonymity 
prosecutor peter wechsung charged that hippenstielinhausen 
played a decisive role in the planning and construction of the 
chemical complex in rabta libya 60 miles southwest of tripoli 
wechsung said hippenstielinhausen shipped to libya documents 
on production as well as measuring and regulating instruments 
to be used by the chemical complex he said investigators had 
concluded that the libyan plant was solely intended for the 
production of poison gases 
wechsung also disclosed that west germanys federal police had 
created a special rabta unit consisting of 20 officials who 
took part in the investigation speaking to reporters in mannheim 
wechsung said about 3000 files containing documents plans and 
other material had been confiscated in the investigation and that 
statements were taken from more than 200 witnesses 
wechsung did not say whether other arrests were expected 
hippenstielimhausen stepped down as head of the company in 
march and was arrested on oct 5 
