<TEXT>
one year after the nations worst oil spill 
hit alaskan waters many us coastal areas face similar threats 
and need tighter standards for tankers pilots and tug escorts two 
environmental groups said today 
the natural resources defense council and the center for marine 
conservation said in independently prepared reports that there are 
many measures not now employed that would help prevent such 
disasters 
we have the knowhow to prevent accidents before they happen 
especially in our most sensitive waters said roger mcmanus 
president of the center for marine conservation 
the studies were undertaken after the tanker exxon valdez ran 
aground and spewed more than 11 million gallons of toxic crude oil 
into prince william sound one year ago saturday 
the natural resources defense council analyzed three of the 
nations busiest ports san francisco new york and los angeles 
each of which handles at least 1000 tanker visits each year 
among the principal recommendations in the two reports are 
requiring oil tankers and barges to have double hulls and 
double bottoms 
requiring tug escorts for tankers in difficult waters and 
biologically sensitive areas 
establishing tankerfree zones in environmentally vulnerable 
areas 
requiring licensed pilots for all tankers and barges over a 
minimum size within harbors 
the groups also recommended that the federal government take 
responsibility immediately for cleanup of major spills and that 
contingency plans be drawn up to prepare for the worst spill that 
could happen 
to date exxon has spent more than 2 billion when a fraction 
of that would have prevented not only the disaster at prince 
william sound but the succeeding spills and groundings in new 
york the florida keys houston and californias huntington 
beach mcmanus said 
the center for marine conservation report urged that the coast 
guard control traffic within 15 miles of the florida keys where a 
series of vessel groundings late last year extensively damaged 
coral reefs it said tankers should avoid certain areas along the 
california coast to protect sensitive wildlife and ecosystems such 
as sea birds kelp beds sea otters and other marine mammals 
in a news conference on wednesday wildlife experts said they 
learned much after the alaska spill but still dont have the 
facilities they will need when more such spills occur 
if there is an oil spill tomorrow we really arent that much 
further ahead in advanced planning than we were a year ago said 
randall davis codirector of international wildlife research in 
san diego 
certainly it will happen again in some form said jay 
holcomb director of the international bird rescue research center 
in berkeley calif oil spills never seem to stop 
davis was in charge of efforts to rescue sea otters and other 
marine mammals after the exxon valdez spill a year ago saturday and 
holcomb led the effort to rescue birds 
they appeared together at a luncheon wednesday at which the 
izaak walton league of america one of the nations oldest 
conservation groups presented an award to procter amp gamble for the 
companys support of the wildlife rescue efforts 
i never want to experience what i saw when we first took our 
boats out in alaska to find birds in a foot deep of oil with their 
heads sticking out yelling and otters crying on the rocks because 
they were covered in oil and were already suffering from the 
ingestion problems holcomb said 
davis said even today we really dont have any permanent 
facility nor any permanent organization to respond to another oil 
spill if it should occur with regards to treating marine mammals 
both said they learned valuable lessons from the alaska 
experience however 
we had never been able to work with some of the species such 
as the horned and tufted puffins beautiful yet nasty birds 
holcomb said we handled 200 or 300 and released quite a few we 
learned some new techniques 
davis said the alaska accident was the first spill to ever 
involve large numbers of marine mammals and sea otters in 
particular we learned a tremendous amount working on that spill 
</TEXT>
