<TEXT>
a major oil spill such as the one that 
devastated alaskas prince william sound a year ago could strike 
new york or los angeles harbor two environmental groups said 
thursday 
one group the center for marine conservation also said spills 
are almost inevitable in the ecologically rich florida keys 
the center and the natural resources defense council in 
separate studies undertaken after the exxon valdez spill in alaska 
called for tighter standards governing tankers pilots and tug 
escorts 
the center suggested that the coast guard establish a network 
much like the airtraffic control system to monitor traffic off 
the florida keys and the central california coast and advise 
mariners of danger spots 
the tanker exxon valdez spewed nearly 11 million gallons of 
toxic crude oil into the sea when it ran aground in prince william 
sound a year ago saturday soaking 1100 miles of scenic coastland 
searchers found 34400 dead birds and believe at least 1000 sea 
otters and countless other animals died 
an exxon valdezsize spill could occur in new york harbor 
the natural resources defense council concluded saying 18 billion 
gallons of oil are brought into the harbor each year and large 
spills have dumped more than 24 million gallons into harbor waters 
in the last 13 years 
the report drew the same conclusion about los angeles harbor 
where it said supertankers regularly arrive carrying 33 million 
gallons of oil it said more than 13 million gallons of oil and 
fuel have spilled into the los angeles harbor area from major and 
medium spills since 1976 
in a case study of san francisco bay the center said the coast 
guard regards it as more difficult to navigate than prince william 
sound and noted that it contains 90 percent of californias coastal 
wetlands the entrance to the bay is ringed with national parkland 
and existing and proposed marine sanctuaries 
the study said tanker traffic is heavy and rising and will 
increase by at least 25 percent if federal plans to lease northern 
and central california offshore areas for oil drilling are approved 
the center for marine conservation said there have been no major 
oil spills in the florida keys for many years except for a spill 
off the marquesas in 1975 from which oil was driven ashore on a 
30mile stretch of the keys 
yet the great number of tankers and other vessels transiting 
the florida straits makes spills a near inevitability given 
historical patterns of tanker casualties the center said 
the center urged that the coast guard control traffic within 15 
miles of the keys where a series of vessel groundings late last 
year extensively damaged coral reefs 
we have the knowhow to prevent accidents before they happen 
especially in our most sensitive waters said roger mcmanus 
president of the center 
among other principal recommendations in the two reports are 
requiring oil tankers and barges to have double hulls and 
double bottoms 
requiring tug escorts for tankers in difficult waters and 
biologically sensitive areas 
establishing tankerfree zones in environmentally vulnerable 
areas 
requiring licensed pilots for all tankers and barges over a a 
minimum size within harbors 
