<TEXT>
america is postponing the day of reckoning 
with its deteriorating road bridge and water network driving the 
eventual repair pricetag even higher congress was told thursday 
while theres little argument it will cost billions of dollars 
to fix the system no consensus has been reached on how to raise 
the money said the office of technology assessment 
as a country we must face the fact that there is no free 
lunch said edith p page the studys project director the 
bad news is we found no silver bullet 
the choices are clear the report said all levels of 
government will have to raise taxes and a variety of fees to pay 
for public works improvements or they will have to eliminate or 
reduce services 
the house and senate public works committees commissioned the 
study and the congressional research office produced a 140page 
report painting a grim picture of transportation and water systems 
weve had a series of reports on this subject each of which 
has been greeted with massive indifference said sen daniel p 
moynihan dny who joined ota officials at a news conference 
i am baffled by this were on the edge at least of 
disinvesting in public works he said 
the report described a public works network fallen into 
disrepair making it difficult for people to get to and from work 
discouraging new plant construction and generally stifling the easy 
movement of products to the marketplace 
a variety of circumstances has conspired to leave the system in 
poor shape the study said including a declining political 
consensus for public works expenditures at all levels of government 
the problem has worsened over the last decade as federal grants 
to states have waned local officials have been reluctant to hike 
taxes and washington has imposed costly new environmental and 
health regulations on industry it said 
two weeks ago president bush announced a national 
transportation policy that would shift more costs to state and 
local governments calling for more toll roads local gas taxes and 
user fees the plan was criticized by some local government 
officials who said their budgets already were stretched to the 
limit 
breaking the logjam created by these issues is no simple 
matter ms page said adding 
although states have increased their investments in public 
works as federal support has dwindled for a variety of reasons no 
state has filled the gap between its infrastructure needs and 
reductions in federal support 
we dont understand that running down the capital 
infrastructure adds to the costs of production she said 
said sen steve symms ridaho we concentrate on efforts in 
raising the costs of doing business in the united states instead of 
lowering the costs of doing business by rebuilding the 
infrastructure 
this disinvestment is going to cost us a lot of money as it 
causes sagging productivity he said 
the study said the nations roughly 83000 local governments 
are in an unenviable position they take the direct political 
heat generated by public works issues 
the ota report made no effort to say how much it would cost to 
repair and modernize aging and deteriorating public works 
facilities but it noted one recent economic projection that if 
spending were increased by 50 billion in the first year 1 
percent of the gross national product productivity would rise 
by 265 billion 
