wartime records concealed for decades show that 
soviet secret police not german invaders murdered thousands of 
polish officers in the katyn pine forest of western russia a 
newspaper reported 
the weekly moscow news used information from official records in 
a twopage article about the katyn forest massacre one of the 
grisliest chapters of the stalin era 
official soviet accounts have said it was the germans who mowed 
down the cream of the polish officer corps held prisoner just 
south of smolensk 
articles published previously have demanded the truth about 
katyn but none documented the soviet role in the deaths of 
thousands of poles 
katyn fostered a deep distrust of the soviets in poland even 
during the four decades it spent as a client state of the kremlin 
a polishsoviet commission investigated the massacre but did not 
issue a formal report 
moscow news concluded the polish officers were killed in the 
spring of 1940 well before the germans invaded the region not in 
1941 as the official version has claimed 
familiarity with the whole set of documents allows one to come 
to the conclusion that the polish officers and police were shot in 
april and may by units of the nkvd a precursor of the kgb it 
said the article was based on research by historian natalia 
lebedeva 
hitlers army invaded western poland on sept 1 1939 starting 
world war ii weeks later the red army marched into eastern poland 
and remained there until the germans pushed them out in 1941 
the newspaper indicated up to 15000 polish officers were killed 
when the nkvd evacuated three prison camps 
most estimates of the number of victims at katyn hover around 
4000 lebedevas reference apparently was to a general operation 
that included execution sites other than the forest 
soon i came to understand that this was not a coincidental 
action but a wellthoughtthrough and carefully planned 
operation said lebedeva who used central national archives and 
soviet army records in her research 
she said it appeared the camps were needed to hold thousands of 
people who would be deported from the three baltic states latvia 
lithuania and estonia after soviet troops moved into them 
the soviet union absorbed the baltic republics to the northwest 
of katyn in 1940 under a secret agreement with germany that 
divided eastern europe into soviet and german spheres of influence 
in the past year or two katyn forest has become a pilgrimage 
site for poles and a group calling itself families of katyn victims 
has thousands of members 
lists published in the moscow news implicate dozens of soviet 
secret police army and government officials in the massacre 
including stalin and lavrenti beria head of the nkvd 
stalin appeared to have held a special grudge against the polish 
officers the article said because his vanity was hurt by the 
polish defeat of soviet troops two decades earlier 
lebedeva said older archivists told her the nkvd tried to take 
over the katyn files in the 1940s but failed she acknowledged 
finding the name katyn only once in the files but said the routes 
to the points where mass graves have been found were laid out 
clearly 
prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki of poland has said the full 
story of the massacre must be told if there to be true friendship 
between poland and the soviet union 
a monument at the site of the mass grave in katyn gives the 
official soviete version of events honoring the victims of 
fascism polish officers shot by the nazis in 1941 
the germans found the mass graves in 1943 and immediately blamed 
the soviet union but the soviets said the nazis murdered the men 
in 1941 during the german march on moscow 
president mikhail s gorbachev and gen wojciech jaruzelski the 
polish leader established the commission of soviet and polish 
historians in 1987 last year the polish members said documents 
indicated there was no doubt the soviets were responsible for the 
katyn massacre 
