<TEXT>
high homicide rates aids and lack of medical 
care are continuing to cut short the lives of black americans 
while the health of whites is improving a government report said 
thursday 
while whites can expect to live to the age of 755 life 
expectancy for blacks is 695 and for black males it is 651 
according to the study 
this concerns us greatly said health and human services 
secretary louis sullivan 
we need to move toward equal health opportunity for our 
citizens including the good health information and the family and 
community support that will help every american make the right 
choices for health and productive lives he said 
healthier living quitting smoking using seat belts reducing 
violence and eating more nutritiously is the key to improving 
health since more than half the causes of premature death are 
related to lifestyle he said 
we have the data to show this pays off this will have more 
effect than any of our medical research he said 
however he added that while lifestyle changes are easily 
articulated as a goal what we dont have enough information on 
yet is how do we most effectively get the information across and 
have people act on it 
the study health united states 1989 is the 14th annual report 
of the health status of the nation 
overall the country improved its infant mortality rate slightly 
to 99 deaths per 1000 live births in 1988 although this rate 
still ranks the united states behind 21 other nations and the gap 
between whites and blacks is widening 
white infants died at the rate of 86 per 1000 live births in 
1987 down 03 points from 1986 during the same period the rate 
for black babies dropped only slightly and at 179 per 1000 births 
is more than twice as high as for whites 
dramatic declines in deaths from heart disease down 33 percent 
between 1970 and 1987 and stroke which was cut in half during the 
period contributed to the increased longevity of americans 
but the gains werent shared equally the decline was greatest 
among white men 35 percent followed by 31 percent for white 
women 28 percent for black women and 24 percent for black men and 
in 1987 the death rate for stroke was twice as high among blacks 
as whites 
health experts say the gaps are not always explained with 
behaviors such as smoking diet homicide and other lifestyle 
factors 
indeed studies show that regardless of the age education or 
marital status of the mother and whether she had early prenatal 
care black woman are generally twice as likely to have a low 
birthweight baby a key factor in infant mortality sullivan said 
also some of the disparity in deaths from stroke cannot be 
explained by lifestyle he said 
the decline in cigarette smoking is accelerating sullivan said 
from 1985 to 1988 cigarette sales dropped about 2 percent a year 
but decreased 6 percent from 1988 to 1989 
however from 1970 to 1987 lung cancer the leading cause of 
death among women increased by 31 percent for white women and 25 
percent for black women 
in 1987 homicide took the lives of seven times more black males 
than white males while the homicide rate for black females was 
more than four times that for white females 
blacks were also lagging in the proportion of mothers receiving 
prenatal care in the first three months of pregnancy for blacks 
the proportion was 61 percent in 1987 compared with 60 percent for 
american indians 76 percent of asian and pacific islanders and 79 
percent for white women 
a growing number of blacks are being diagnosed with acquired 
immune deficiency syndrome increasing from 25 percent to 29 
percent of all aids cases between 1984 and 1988 as of last 
september blacks made up 55 percent of all aids cases among 
children under age 13 and hispanics accounted for 21 percent 
