<TEXT>
president bush implored the soviet union 
thursday not to use force to block lithuanias secession but also 
urged the breakaway republic to recognize certain realities of 
moscows control 
commending the kremlin for dealing peacefully with changes in 
eastern europe bush said please continue to exercise that kind 
of restraint and remember no use of force he said both sides 
should negotiate their differences 
separately defense secretary dick cheney said any resort to 
military might would do great violence to the reforms being 
championed by soviet president mikhail s gorbachev 
the presidents comments came as soviet armored personnel 
carriers and trucks drove through the lithuanian capital in a show 
of force bush declined to criticize gorbachev for demanding that 
lithuanians surrender their guns they should talk about that 
bush said 
bush also refused to say how he would react if force were used 
what possible good would come from the president of the united 
states standing halfway around the world speculating on something 
that he doesnt want to see happen 
he issued his plea for restraint during a 20minute news 
conference on the white house lawn 
bush stood beneath a towering oak tree and next to a flowering 
eastern redbud tree that he and his wife barbara had just planted 
commenting on two days of talks with visiting polish prime 
minister tadeusz mazowiecki bush said there was no need for soviet 
troops to be stationed in poland or anywhere else in eastern 
europe and the sooner they get out of there the better he 
said 
bush acknowledged a nuance of difference with mazowiecki 
over the prime ministers demands that the two germanys sign a 
treaty guaranteeing polish borders before they unite but he said 
the poles and germans are very very close now to an 
understanding that the current borders must remain intact 
on another sensitive foreign policy issue bush disputed 
contentions that he contributed to the fall of the government of 
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir with comments linking israeli 
settlements in east jerusalem with those in the west bank and gaza 
most people in israel understood that i was simply reiterating 
a standing united states policy one that i feel very strong 
about 
on other issues bush 
said he wants a treaty to cut soviet and american troops in 
europe to be ready by the time of his summit this summer with 
gorbachev in washington another oficial said bush had meant to say 
he wanted to have a strategicarms treaty ready by the summit bush 
said the summit date had not been set but should be pinned down 
soon 
said he will not attend the april 25 inauguration of 
usbacked presidentelect violeta chamorro in nicaragua but wants 
to visit the country sometime 
responding to another question bush said im dying to go to 
australia and wants to make the trip before the end of the year he 
declined to say he would go to new zealand during such a trip 
noting us unhappiness over its refusal to permit american 
warships carrying nuclear weapons in its waters 
refused to discuss texas republican gubernatorial candidate 
clayton williams concerns about running against a woman calling 
himself an expert on the subject because of his race against 
democrat geraldine ferraro in 1984 bush said i know exactly 
what he means and i refuse to elaborate on it for fear of 
complicating his life 
prodded congress to speed approval of 800 million in aid for 
panama and nicaragua 
in recent days the united states has expressed concern about 
soviet moves in lithuania which declared independence from moscow 
on march 11 after the ruling communists were removed from power in 
free elections however the united states has not extended formal 
diplomatic recognition saying lithuania does not control its 
territory 
in his remarks bush noted that the united states had never 
recognized the forced incorporation of lithuania or the other 
baltic states of estonia and latvia into the soviet union in 1940 
however there are certain realities in life bush said 
the lithuanians are well aware of them and they should talk as 
they are with the soviet officials about these differences 
he said he was pleased that soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze had said moscow would not use force 
it is very important that force not be used bush said 
but i believe that they can talk and work out these problems 
asked if he thought gorbachev was guilty of intimidation by 
demanding that lithuanians surrender their arms bush said i 
would prefer to put emphasis on his statement that there will be no 
use of force and thats where im going to keep the emphasis and 
keep reminding every party to this discussion over there no use 
of force 
meanwhile state department spokesman richard boucher said that 
moscows order to tighten visa controls in lithuania and expel 
foreigners contradicts the soviets commitment to a more open 
society and to contact between countries 
were concerned by the order to have internal security and 
secret police troops seize private sporting guns unless they are 
surrendered he said adding that the soviets are trying to 
suggest there is a threat to public order from lithuanians 
we believe however that the lithuanians are committed to a 
peaceful resolution of their differences with the soviet union the 
lithuanian people have shown their commitment to nonviolence and 
democracy boucher said 
