<TEXT>
exxon valdez captain joseph hazelwood 
was acquitted today of three major charges and convicted of one 
misdemeanor in the nations worst oil spill 
the single charge of which hazelwood was convicted negligent 
discharge of oil carries a maximum sentence of 90 days in jail 
and a 1000 fine far less than the 7 years and 61000 fine he 
could have faced 
there were bursts of applause in the court room as superior 
court judge karl johnstone read the first three verdicts of not 
guilty 
hazelwoods lawyers patted him on the back and for the first 
time in the long trial the normally solemn defendant smiled 
broadly 
the jurors delivering their verdict two days before the first 
anniversary of the disaster absolved hazelwood of all charges 
alleging that he was drunk and reckless when the tanker ran 
aground spilling nearly 11 million gallons of oil into prince 
william sound 
the jurors reached their verdict after only 10 hours of 
deliberations 
earlier the jury signaled they were close to a unanimous 
decision by deciding to skip going out to lunch they ordered food 
sent into the jury room so they could continue their talks through 
the lunch hour 
but at noon johnstone emerged from his chambers and told 
reporters the panel has reached its verdict 
the panel which ended its first day of deliberations wednesday 
without reaching a verdict sought a series of blood alcohol charts 
and graphs used by a defense expert to illustrate his testimony 
johnstone after conferring in a hurried session with attorneys 
sent the jury a note saying you have received all of the 
evidence the exhibits you have requested are not in evidence 
the jurors returned to their task today checking in promptly at 
830 am a bailiff escorted them to their jury room and they began 
their talks for a second day the trial is in its seventh week 
meanwhile an alternate juror who was dismissed once the regular 
jury began its deliberations told the alaska public radio network 
she would have acquitted hazelwood of all charges 
terry turner an anchorage bookkeeper said she doubts the 
skipper was drunk while in command 
there were 21 witnesses who said there was no sign of 
impairment she said 
she added that she believed hazelwood had expected a normal 
transit of prince william sound on the night of the march 24 
grounding which might explain his decision to leave the ships 
bridge 
asked whether she believed hazelwood was drunk she said no 
i dont think he was there was a lot more to it than that we 
had a drunk captain running into a reef they really didnt have 
evidence of it 
ms turner said she felt hazelwoods loss of his job and the 
impact on his life was sufficient punishment for whatever role he 
had in the disaster 
i dont think he was totally to blame she said i hope a 
lot of the other jurors feel that way 
saturday will be the first anniversary of the disaster in which 
the 987foot tanker rammed the charted reef in prince william 
sount gushing nearly 11 million gallons of north slope crude oil 
the spill wreaked devastation on birds fish and wildlife and 
coated hundreds of miles of rocky shoreline 
the exhibits sought by the jury wednesday were used by defense 
lawyers during the trial to help illustrate testimony by michael 
hlastala a physiologist who discussed blood testing for alcohol 
they showed the various absorption and burnoff rates of alcohol in 
the human body 
defense attorney dick madson said the charts were not placed in 
evidence because jurors might have been unable to decipher them 
without the accompanying testimony 
hlastala of the university of washington in seattle had branded 
as nonsense prosecution efforts to figure out hazelwoods blood 
alcohol level based on a blood test taken 10 hours after the march 
24 grounding 
the prosecution sought to prove that the fired exxon skipper was 
drunk when his ship went aground at bligh reef while hazelwood was 
below 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny is charged with one felony 
seconddegree criminal mischief and three misdemeanors reckless 
endangerment operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent 
discharge of oil he could receive 7 years in prison and 61000 
in fines if convicted 
the jurys note disclosed that they chose an insurance broker to 
serve as forewoman in deliberations the jury includes homemakers 
a real estate agent an accountant a postman and an air traffic 
controller 
johnstone said he would allow the jurors to continue their talks 
over the weekend if they should fail to reach verdicts by friday 
</TEXT>
