<TEXT>
the house banking committee on thursday 
approved plans designed to crack down on banks that allow 
themselves to be used in the moneylaundering operations of drug 
pushers 
money is the vehicle that drives the drug trade chairman 
henry b gonzalez dtexas said as the committee approved the bill 
480 
the measure would require federal regulators to hold a hearing 
on whether to close any bank convicted with its directors and 
officers of money laundering or related offenses the charter could 
be revoked or regulators could appoint a conservator to operate the 
bank 
federal officials already have the power to close banks 
convicted of money laundering however the hearings outlined in 
the bill would set the machinery in motion sponsors said 
lawmakers have expressed heightened concern about money 
laundering under which huge drug profits are hidden by 
transferring them through caribbean tax havens and other centers of 
banking secrecy before they are returned to the united states and 
invested in legitimate businesses 
a similar bill was introduced in the senate on wednesday 
banks that knowingly handle dirty drug money should not be 
permitted to do business in this country said sen john kerry 
dmass 
gonzalez described the house plan as a compromise that would not 
only punish those who ignore money laundering but also provide due 
process for bankers 
he hailed reps frank annunzio dill thomas r carper 
rdel and bill mccollum rfla for working out a compromise 
annunzio cited estimates that worldwide drug profits could total 
300 billion a year 
the vast quantities of cash may provide drug dealers with 
their greatest vulnerability to detection he said the drug 
dealer is caught in a neverending blizzard of cash every day 
the bill calls for removal of bank officials convicted of money 
laundering or structuring transactions to evade requirements of the 
bank secrecy act those convicted would be prohibited from 
affiliating with other financial institutions 
the measure would require the treasury department to establish 
regulations aimed at halting money laundering by wire transfer it 
would raise the fine for negligent noncompliance with 
moneylaundering reporting requirements from 500 to 5000 
</TEXT>
