<TEXT>
after a year of accusations against faceless villains exxon 
and oilrelated agencies the hazelwood trial provided a human 
side to the exxon valdez calamity focusing on frailties of captain 
and crew 
although 150 civil suits were filed and exxon was indicted in 
federal court hazelwood was the only individual charged 
criminally his lawyers complained he was a scapegoat in a 
disaster with many culprits 
his trial in anchorage superior court had the elements of an 
engrossing sea story with a dark subplot involving liquor troubled 
crew members and a starcrossed captain whose battles with the 
bottle were well known 
but the skipper who had been painted as a liquor swigging 
brigand turned out to be a quiet figure intent on nothing more 
than blending into the woodwork he sat back stroking his beard 
while others addressed the trials key questions was the skipper 
drunk on duty and was he reckless to leave the ships bridge 
whether hazelwood was drunk when his ship grounded remained a 
muddled issue because authorities failed to do a timely blood 
alcohol test when they got around to it 10 hours after the 
grounding hazelwood had a 061 alcohol reading lower than the 
alaska standard of 10 for drunken driving 
a prosecution expert witness tried to calculate backward and 
concluded that hazelwood had a blood alcohol reading of 14 when 
the ship grounded but defense experts ridiculed the figures as 
nonsense saying results could not be conclusive because there 
was too long a wait before the test and too many variables 
including whether hazelwood drank after the grounding 
hazelwood who chose not to testify never explained 
in six weeks of testimony witnesses came forward to tell what 
they knew of the day the exxon valdez and hazelwood sailed into 
history 
it was the thursday before good friday and the tanker had 
pulled into its namesake port of valdez to pick up a load of oil 
hazelwood went ashore for lunch with two crew members and a local 
pilot they remember that he sipped iced tea then they separated 
to do shopping 
later in the day the hour remained in dispute hazelwood met 
with his pals at the pipeline club a bar where they said he drank 
three vodkas in about three hours a woman patron of the club wife 
of a coast guard investigator in the case placed hazelwood there 
much earlier drinking for seven hours but her testimony never was 
corroborated 
on the way back to the ship the men stopped and bought pizza 
for the crew and hazelwood had another drink either beer or vodka 
when they arrived at the valdez terminal about 820 pm they 
learned that the sailing time originally set for 10 pm had been 
moved up to 9 pm the prosecution would maintain that hazelwoods 
tardiness in boarding his ship showed recklessness 
was the skipper intoxicated he showed no signs of it during 
the trial not a single witness said he appeared drunk 
did he stagger defense attorneys would ask did he slur 
his words inevitably the answers were no 
pilot william murphy who guided the tanker through the valdez 
narrows said he noticed a trace of alcohol on hazelwoods breath 
after a halfhour on the bridge he said the skipper went below and 
remained there for an hour when murphy left the ship at about 
1030 pm he conferred with hazelwood i reminded him there was 
ice reported ahead 
the crucial period recounted repeatedly in testimony began at 
1153 pm when hazelwood decided to leave the bridge in control of 
third mate gregory cousins after discussing maneuvers that would 
take the exxon valdez out of shipping lanes to avoid ice then turn 
back to the lanes before leaving prince william sound 
he asked if i felt comfortable with what we were going to do 
and i said yes recalled cousins he said do you feel 
comfortable enough that i can go below and get rid of some 
paperwork i said i felt very comfortable 
the prosecution would note that cousins did not have the special 
endorsement hazelwood had for piloting in prince william sound a 
license the defense claimed was mere formality and had been waived 
by the coast guard 
at the helm was robert kagan a seaman who had problems with 
steering in the past many witnesses would blame kagan for ramming 
the oilfilled tanker into a charted reef 
cousins said he ordered kagan to make a 10degree right rudder 
turn a routine order but he failed to check until it was too late 
to see if the turn had been made by then the exxon valdez was 
steaming toward bligh reef 
ten minutes after hazelwood left the bridge cousins glanced at 
the rudder indicator and i could tell we hadnt turned i 
think mr kagan didnt really understand the command 
cousins called hazelwood in his cabin 
i told him that we were getting into serious trouble 
the third mate recalled that was then we suffered the first 
shock and we were hard aground 
deep holes were gashed in the ships underbelly she was impaled 
on a rock the size of a volkswagen and warm oil was bubbling into 
the cold clear waters of prince william sound in all the ship 
belched out nearly 11 million gallons of alaska north slope crude 
oil in a hemorrhage that killed countless birds fish and wildlife 
on the richly populated sound the rocky shore turned black for 
hundreds of miles 
whats the problem a coast guard investigator asked 
hazelwood upon boarding the crippled ship 
i think youre looking at it said the captain in a comment 
which planted the idea that the skipper was accepting blame his 
lawyers would say that was his training talking a captain always 
takes responsibility for his ship 
one issue which consumed half the trial was whether hazelwood 
in the frantic moments after grounding tried to drive his ship off 
the reef he denied it but prosecutors tried to show he risked 
capsizing the tanker and killing the crew 
the issue became moot when the defense proved the ship was 
immovable and the judge agreed hazelwood could not be convicted of 
trying something that was impossible 
</TEXT>
