from the senate this year mitchell maintained earlier in the week 
on wednesday night byrd offered to lower the packages expected 
cost from 700 million over four years to 500 million over three 
years now he said he would retreat no further 
im not going to stand here and say ive got 51 votes needed 
for passage but i can tell you you dont have 51 votes either 
and i can tell you im very close byrd told mitchell as debate 
on the issue continued late into the night wednesday 
byrd complained that the white house had been unwilling to 
negotiate with him so ive negotiated with myself originally 
byrd had sought a much broader aid package which could have cost 
16 billion over six years 
byrd argued that coal miners should be singled out for help 
because the bill which calls for reducing sulfur dioxide emissions 
from electric utilities by 10 million tons a year by the end of the 
decade takes direct aim at these workers 
industry has argued forcefully among senators in recent weeks 
