lew allen jr will retire sept 30 as 
director of jet propulsion laboratory capping a career in which he 
guided nasas unmanned space program the air force and the 
supersecret national security agency 
im delighted to be able to leave at a time when the future of 
the space program looks very bright and the activities at jpl in 
connection with the exploration of the solar system look very 
promising indeed allen said wednesday 
jpls magellan spacecraft will reach venus in august the 
galileo spacecraft is bound for a 1995 rendezvous with jupiter 
mars observer is set for launch in 1992 and the lab is gearing up 
for future lunar and mars explorations under president bushs space 
initiative 
allen 64 a physicist said he and his wife would like to 
travel some and smell the roses a bit when he retires on his 65th 
birthday 
he has spent eight years as jpl director and vice president of 
the california institute of technology caltech operates the 
laboratory for the national aeronautics and space administration 
allen oversaw the voyager 2 spacecrafts explorations of uranus 
in 1986 and neptune last summer and the completion of the 198283 
survey of heatemitting objects in space by the infrared 
astronomical satellite 
allen retired in 1982 as a general and air force chief of staff 
a post that made him a member of the joint chiefs of staff the 
presidents principal military advisers president carter named 
allen to that post in 1978 
in 1973 president nixon appointed allen director of the 
national security agency which reportedly has the largest budget 
of any us intelligence agency and operates much of americas 
network of spy satellites and electronic surveillance he held that 
post until 1977 when he was named head of air force systems 
command 
