cone mills said wednesday it was shutting down its 450employee 
american spinning plant in greenville sc 
meanwhile milliken said it would close a mill in robbins sc 
putting 255 people out of work and would eliminate 129 jobs from 
its drayton mill in spartanburg sc 
a statement issued to milliken employees wednesday afternoon 
said that while all of us have worked very hard to be successful 
with our customers it has not been enough to overcome the massive 
continuing growth of imported textile products into the united 
states 
this huge and escalating textile import burden has directly 
impacted the drayton plant and made it impossible for that plant to 
continue full operations a company statement said 
cone mills chairman dewey trogdon also cited imports in the 
closing the american spinning plant he also blamed rising fiber 
costs and the plants multistoried layout which made it 
impractical to install more modern equipment 
employees learned of their job losses as the house textile 
caucus launched a new campaign for legislation to curb imports of 
textiles and apparel 
milliken spokesman terry may and cone mills spokesman jim butner 
said the cutbacks had been considered for several weeks but both 
said the announcements were not timed to coincide with the textile 
caucuss decision to introduce a textile bill 
layoffs at the milliken plants will begin in about 60 days but 
may said he did not know when they would be completed the cutback 
at the drayton plant will still leave about 90 employees on the job 
may said the plant will continue to make yarns used in mens and 
womens clothing 
the displaced workers would be able to transfer to other 
milliken plants without loss of seniority or benefits according to 
the company statement 
cone mills layoffs will begin in late may and will be completed 
by the end of june butner said 
cone mills is one of the nations largest producers of denims 
and corduroys it employs about 9000 workers at 15 plants in the 
carolinas and mississippi and has annual sales around 700 million 
butner said 
milliken has estimated sales of 25 billion a year the company 
has 14300 employees at 55 plants in the carolinas georgia canada 
and europe 
