union that will increase the annual minimum shipments of us grain 
to the soviets to 10 million metric tons from nine million tons 
under the current agreement 
under the agreement the soviets are committed to buy at least 
four million tons each of wheat and feed grains but moscow can 
substitute up to 750000 tons of one commodity for the other 
the deal was viewed as bullish for grain prices but was 
overshadowed by the sharp drop in stock prices 
