<TEXT>
the 25th floor of the south tower of the 
luxurious world financial center is empty save for a few boxes so 
are the 26th 27th and 28th floors 
in the booming mid1980s merrill lynch amp co expected to fill 
the space easily the nations largest securities firm booked two 
full towers in the ultramodern complex in lower manhattan that 
opened in 1986 using conservative estimates of employment growth 
then merrill scaled back to one tower plus about half the 
second after the 1987 stock market crash even that was too much 
and now the firm plans to sublet nine floors including the four 
undeveloped ones 
on wall street and broad street and greenwich street and 
battery place a securities industry recession has created an 
officespace glut in the worlds premier financial district 
vacancy rates are soaring in the maze of silver office towers 
and aging stone monoliths where stock trading began almost 200 
years ago under a buttonwood tree property brokers compare the 
slump to the mid1970s when new york teetered on bankruptcy 
were still headed south said robert fr ballard an 
executive vice president with the real estate firm cushman amp 
wakefield who has worked in the wall street building market since 
1959 we havent bottomed out yet 
manhattan real estate brokers say the vacancy rate in the 
downtown financial district is approaching 20 percent vs 8 
percent to 12 percent in 1985 during the securities industry boom 
put another way the 14 million square feet of available office 
space downtown equals three empty buildings each as big as a 
110story world trade center tower 
the glut is expected to worsen because hundreds of thousands of 
square feet to be abandoned by firms such as merrill shearson 
lehman hutton inc salomon inc and collapsed drexel burnham 
lambert inc havent been tallied yet 
unprecedented growth in stock trading and investment banking 
gave rise to handoverfist hiring and expansion by wall street 
firms in the 1980s 
average daily trading volume on the new york stock exchange shot 
up from 322 million shares in 1979 to 189 million shares in 1987 
while employment in in new yorks securities and commodities 
industries grew from 74 million to 163 million 
during that period wall street firms set ambitious expansion 
plans tied to the seemingly limitless possibilities of another 
boom building world headquarters seemed logical to accomodate 
technological advances that required more space for more computers 
for more trading into the 21st century 
many of the financial firms dont indulge in what we call 
intelligent strategic planning regarding their space needs said 
joel wechsler a managing director of the real estate firm edward 
s gordon amp co theyre getting a little more sophisticated in 
that area now 
stock market volume securities underwriting mergers and 
takeovers and other financial businesses are down sharply since 
the crash the securities industry has lost more than 40000 jobs 
the vacancy rates are directly related to the shrinkage in the 
financial services industry said anthony m saytanides edward 
s gordons chief operating officer 
ballard put it less gently the developers built too much 
space the tenants rented too much space the market took a 
nosedive 
during the decline several projects were abandoned and other 
overly ambitious ones have cost firms hundreds of millions of 
dollars salomon took a 150 million accounting charge against 
earnings after dropping out of a major project two firms that 
named buildings for themselves ef hutton amp co and thomson 
mckinnon securities inc are history 
shearson the no 2 brokerage behind merrill spent 450 million 
to build a 39story office tower known as shearson lehman hutton 
plaza the firm plans to fill the building which opened late last 
year but also is firing up to 5000 workers this year which could 
lead to more unused space 
workers in reduced shearson departments say they can roam floors 
almost undisturbed the firms new tower is adorned with a 
parthenonlike frieze and some wags say it too could wind up a 
monument to a golden age 
there may be some discussion in hindsight whether it was the 
most effective use of the firms money at the time a shearson 
official privately conceded adding that it is evaluating space 
needs as part of an overhaul 
merrill decided to move in the early 80s when its headcount 
was growing by 13 percent annually it booked the world financial 
center space anticipating only half that growth but since the 
crash merrill has slashed its work force back to a 1980 level 
more cuts are planned 
the firm took a 470 million charge against earnings last 
quarter for its restructuring 220 million to cover real estate 
commitments nearly all of that in new york 
the growth has certainly gone in the other direction 
merrill spokesman fred yager said our fixed costs have been 
reduced considerably and one of our biggest fixed costs is real 
estate 
for the real estate market the gluts the thing while modern 
office spaces such as the world financial center and world trade 
center complexes are almost fully occupied older buildings are 
bearing the brunt as firms move out 
the average asking rent downtown is falling but not in 
proportion to available space brokers say topline offices still 
command around 35 per square foot among the highest in the 
country some prices for older buildings though have fallen into 
the single digits just like in the 1970s 
brokers estimate the downtown vacancy rate will climb well above 
20 percent once a rash of moves some across new york waterways to 
cheaper brooklyn or new jersey are completed in the mid70s 
the rate was about 25 percent brokers said 
among the untallied moves the securities industry automation 
corps move to new quarters abandoning 200000 square feet 
salomons shift to 7 world trade center leaving 500000 square 
feet behind the consolidation by merrill and shearson and about 
15 million square feet by drexel 
during its junkbond driven heyday drexel planned to build new 
headquarters downtown the firm wisely scrapped the project after 
settling securities fraud charges with the government last april 
and trimming 4000 employees by selling its retail brokerage 
operations 
