<TEXT>
eastern airlines and its pilots union have agreed 
to an interim contract calling for a 25 percent wage cut and 
benefit concessions the company announced thursday 
the pact did not resolve the issue of rehiring more of the 
pilots who engaged in a sympathy strike with the machinists union 
in march 1989 
eastern also insisted it needs twice the amount of concessions 
given in the interim pact by the time the contract expires on july 
1 to successfully emerge from chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings 
time to resolve the dispute regrettably has just about run 
out in light of the reorganization timetable said thomas j 
matthews senior vice president of human resources for eastern 
which is owned by texas air corp 
eastern insisted federal mediators would have to continue 
efforts to reach a permanent agreement to cut costs further 
if expedited mediation is not successful in leading to such an 
arrangement eastern will have to promptly seek bankruptcy 
court permission to achieve full cost reductions on a longterm 
basis the carrier said in a news release 
the interim cut applies to easterns approximately 850 pilots 
still being paid at the prestrike wage rate of about 72000 
eastern had 3600 union pilots who honored picket lines when the 
machinists went on strike on march 4 1989 since then many pilots 
have returned replacements have been hired at lower wages and the 
airline has sold many routes 
edward breen spokesman for the eastern air line pilots 
association contended the company intends to use the temporary 
agreement negotiated with the help of the national mediation 
board as a device to crush the union 
he said that by demanding more concessions in advance eastern 
hoped to push the talks into a final impasse 
breen said alpa executives had agreed in principle to the 
contract but it would not be signed until after a formal vote of 
the master executive committee on saturday in washington 
the 25 percent wage cuts exclude about 950 replacement pilots 
hired at an average 27500 when the strike began 
the new wage levels are among the lowest in the country for 
major carriers breen said 
an eastern pilot after this will make about 50 percent of what 
a united airlines pilot makes and they still cant make a 
profit he said 
eastern lost 2826 million in the last quarter of 1989 
bringing total losses for the year to 8523 million overall 
houstonbased texas air lost 8856 million 
the interim agreement also calls for a reduction in the 
airlines contribution to the pilots pension plan increased pilot 
contributions to their medical and dental insurance and the 
preservation of tougher work rules in effect since the strike 
easterns alpa contract expired in june 1988 but its provisions 
had remained in effect federal mediators have guided negotiations 
since september although eastern said the two sides have been 
consulting regularly for 33 months 
under easterns reorganization plan pilots will have to reduce 
their wages and benefits to the same degree as other employees 
matthews said 
