<TEXT>
a federal judge on thursday delayed accepting a 
guilty plea from general development corp and ordered an 
independent expert to review a plan to monitor the company and 
repay thousands of people allegedly overcharged for its homes 
us district judge lenore nesbitt gave conditional acceptance 
to guilty pleas from the miamibased home builder and two former 
executives pending review of presentencing reports 
general development former president robert ehrling and former 
chairman david brown were named last week in a 16count indictment 
alleging a sevenyear scheme to sell overvalued homes at its nine 
florida communities 
the indictment claims the company priced homes well above 
comparable residences in florida and kept prospective buyers from 
learning about the difference most of the general development 
customers were northeast and midwest residents brought to florida 
on heavily subsidized trips 
reading from prepared statements in court both ehrling and 
brown apologized and admitted their knowledge of the pricehike 
scheme the company allegedly sold 10000 overpriced homes for 850 
million from 1982 to 1989 
i am truly sorry i did not take action sooner and im sorry 
for the customers who were misled said brown 
under the plea agreement with federal prosecutors the two 
executives and the company would plead guilty to one fraud count 
while the 15 additional counts would be dismissed charges against 
gdv financial corp a general development subsidiary that provided 
mortgages and financial aid to homeowners would be dropped said 
assistant us attorney norman moscowitz 
if ms nesbitt accepts the guilty pleas from brown 49 and 
ehrling 50 each could face up to five years in prison a 250000 
fine and restitution payments sentencing is scheduled for may 22 
brown and ehrling were making 600000 a year each before they 
were forced out by general development directors march 9 after the 
company disclosed it was facing indictment 
general developments estimated 100 million 25year 
restitution program is detailed in a civil consent decree that 
prosecutors expect to file within the next week 
ms nesbitt said she wants an expert perhaps a former trustee 
of a dissolved corporation to review the consent decree for its 
feasibility 
i dont want to accept something now and be locked in she 
said 
a hearing on the consent decree is scheduled for april 3 
the company also could face a maximum 500000 fine for its 
guilty plea 
in court moscowitz said general development priced its homes an 
average of 40 percent higher than market value and lot prices were 
inflated by up to 10 times up to half of the general development 
homebuyers were from the new york metropolitan area he said 
the indictment also alleges general development kept customers 
from learning about other homes prices in florida by assigning a 
sales representatives to stay with the people constantly and even 
to screen their calls in some cases 
the 35yearold company has sold or has available 350000 lots 
in florida and also operates a timeshare resort near walt disney 
world a recreational community in tennessee and 10 timeshare 
resorts in the west 
general development recently laid off 5500 workers about 10 
percent of its work force and shut sales offices in hollywood 
fla and boston 
the company is also the target of several classaction suits 
involving thousands of homebuyers alleging overpricing 
in delaware chancery court a general development shareholder 
filed suit last week seeking a court order to nominate three 
candidates to the board of directors in may and three others in 
1991 
general development claims new yorkbased united capital corp 
which owns about 127 percent of its outstanding shares missed the 
filing deadline for this years corporate elections and that 
directors can appoint people to the 1991 vacancies 
the delaware suit alleges brown persuaded united capital 
chairman attilio petrocelli to sign a letter dropping the proxy 
slate in exchange for permission to acquire up to 20 percent of 
general development stock but brown failed to disclose the 
companys financial problems and the pending indictments the suit 
alleges 
the suit seeks to nullify the agreement and restore united 
capitals proxy slate 
</TEXT>
