<TEXT>
the italian senate on thursday passed a bill that 
would restrict ownership of television and newspapers and ban 
commercials during film opera and theater productions on 
television 
the measure is seen as a major threat to the television empire 
of italian media tycoon silvio berlusconi 
the bill approved by a show of hands in the senate must be 
considered next week by the chamber of deputies the lower house of 
parliament 
the tv law would prevent those who own more than 16 percent of 
italys total newspaper circulation from owning a television 
station those who control from 8 percent to 16 percent of the 
circulation would be restricted to just one television station and 
those who own up to 8 percent of the circulation could own two 
stations someone who does not own a newspaper could own up to 
three television stations 
italy is the only european nation without a law regulating 
television ownership 
under the bill berlusconi could be forced to give up one of his 
three tv stations or his newspapers 
the rome daily la repubblica which berlesconi controls through 
his acquisition of mondadori editore estimated he could lose up to 
320 million a year in advertising if the amendment on commercials 
passes 
gianni letta a spokesman for berlusconis holding company 
fininvest said wednesday that approval of the amendment would 
mean the end of commercial television in italy to the advantage of 
a monopoly by staterun rai 
the staterun television carries advertising but mainly between 
shows 
</TEXT>
