<DOCNO> AP900322-0245 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
southland corp with its announcement thursday 
that it was selling out to a japanese firm became the latest 
company forced to seek outside help after being swamped by 
leveraged buyout debt 
the parent of 7000 7eleven convenience stores said it was 
selling a controlling interest to itoyokado co ltd japans 
secondlargest supermarket operator and a partner in the 49 
billion buyout of southland in 1987 for 400 million and the 
assumption of southlands debt 
southland joined the growing ranks of companies such as campeau 
corp revco ds inc and doskocil cos that were unable to handle 
the large debt bills run up in takeover deals 
their stories have common elements a debtfinanced buyout made 
during the rosy days of the 1980s takeover binge disappointing 
sales and earnings that cant support massive interest payments 
assets put up for sale to bring in desperatelyneeded cash 
economists are predicting that as time goes on more companies 
will find themselves in similar straits especially if the already 
slowing economy takes a downturn 
finding an outside investor as southland has done is one 
option a struggling company has for getting out of trouble the 
infusion of cash and assumption of debt brings an immediate end to 
the financial crisis but the price in this case a loss of 
corporate control can be high 
for other companies including revco campeau and doskocil 
the answer has been bankruptcy court protection 
revco one of the countrys biggest drugstore chains went 
private in a 15 billion junk bondfinanced buyout in 1986 it was 
the first big leveraged buyout to fail and revco is selling 
hundreds of stores as it reorganizes 
campeau was unable to handle a 7 billion debt load after buying 
allied stores corp and federated department stores inc again 
with highinterest junk bond financing when news of the companys 
troubles broke in september it set off a plunge in the junk bond 
market and helped bring the debtfinanced takeover boom to an end 
campeau placed the store businesses in bankruptcy court in 
january 
doskocil a food processing company defaulted on a 133 million 
loan after taking over the much larger wilson foods corp doskocil 
has been unable to find a buyer for assets it has tried to sell 
and the higher prices it has been forced to pay for raw materials 
has left it short of cash 
the company sought bankruptcy court protection from creditors 
earlier this month 
all of these companies when they went heavily into debt 
indicated they could handle the payments but the economy has 
slowed profits have fallen and interest rates have moved higher 
leaving some highlyleveraged operations in a bind 
retailers have been particularly vulnerable as several of tese 
firms illustrate the retail industry has been in a slump for 
several years and an expected improvement never materialized what 
looked like a great investment two years ago is todays bad deal 
some economists have warned the economy eventually could run 
into trouble because of highlyleveraged businesses 
companies that do business with financiallydistressed concerns 
may find they arent being paid for merchandise they have shipped 
or arent receiving as many orders they may have to cut back and 
possibly lay off workers as a result 
furthermore a company strapped by debt could be limited in its 
ability to compete and might lose market share to other concerns 
including foreign businesses a drop in market share means less 
demand for a companies products which also can mean lost jobs 
</TEXT>
