<TEXT>
shawmut national corp has revised its 1989 
earnings after an examination by federal bank regulators posting a 
129 million loss for the year instead of a previously announced 
200 million profit 
the bank revised its fourthquarter statement to reflected a 
327 million loss instead of a 39 million profit it also 
announced wednesday that it had lowered its dividend per share to 
25 cents from 36 cents 
the revision was another sign of the troubles facing banks 
because of the slumping real estate market examinations of real 
estate lending led to a 11 billion loss at bank of new england 
corp earlier this year 
investors seemed unconcerned by shawmuts move which could be 
viewed as protecting the bank against future problems shawmut 
stock gained 37 cents thursday to close at 1525 in new york 
stock exchange trading 
shawmut one of new englands largest banking companies said 
bad loans for the fourth quarter jumped sharply to 1234 million 
from 464 million 
after the review by federal regulators shawmut which is based 
in boston and hartford and has more than 400 branches said it 
nearly doubled the size of its reserves for loan losses at the end 
of 1989 to 739 million from 383 million 
bank examiners convinced shawmut to post the loss shawmut had 
called in 180 examiners from three federal agencies in a 
confidencebuilding effort after federal officials gave both bank 
of new england and bank of boston poor marks 
examinations of new england banks have drawn fire with bank 
officials accusing the examiners of being excessively harsh after 
failing to nip the savings and loan crisis in the bud 
shawmut chairman and chief executive officer joel alvord said 
the examiners had not changed the regulations but were calling 
the plays a little tighter 
when you see clouds on the horizon you carry an umbrella 
alvord said we may see showers but others might see storm 
clouds or a torrential downpour 
shawmut also said it expected a 40 million firstquarter 1990 
profit but that the figured would include 56 million in onetime 
gains and tax benefits 
news of the revision prompted both standard and poors corp and 
fitch investors service inc to lower their credit ratings of the 
banks senior debt issues to take the greater risk into account 
