<TEXT>
the state of connecticut on thursday 
joined with striking workers managers and private investors to buy 
the firearms division of colt industries giving the 154yearold 
gunmaker new life after a bitter fouryear strike 
state treasurer francisco l borges said the state would put up 
25 million from pension funds for a 47 percent stake in a newly 
created company to be called colts manufacturing company 
let me emphasize that this is a carefully thought out 
carefully structured potentially very profitable business 
venture borges said the states participation is not a 
bailout not a handout and not a subsidy 
union members whitecollar workers and investors also will hold 
stakes in the company which colt industries decided to sell in 
order to concentrate on its larger aerospace automotive and 
industrial services businesses 
the new companys first official act was to write a check for 
10 million in back pay for 1050 workers who had been on strike 
since jan 24 1986 about 50 striking workers applauded when the 
company produced the check at a news conference in borges office 
under terms of the buyout the company will pay a total of 13 
million in back wages to settle an unfair labor practices lawsuit 
brought by the united auto workers union against colt industries in 
the wake of the strike 
strikers will be put back to work based on seniority in 
addition to back pay they will receive a 13 percent wage increase 
and a stock plan that will allow united auto workers members to own 
115 percent of the stock in the new company 
in return for the back pay the uaw dropped its lawsuit against 
colt industries for unfair labor practices 
the national labor relations board said the settlement was the 
largest in its 55year history topping a 12 million settlement in 
1979 to chemical plant workers in westwego la 
salaried workers will own about 12 percent of the shares in 
colts manufacturing while the investor group cf holding corp 
will own about 12 percent said antony autorino chairman of cf 
holding corp 
colt industries put the firearms division up for sale 11 months 
ago at the time the division was ravaged by a threeyearold 
strike and had just lost the contract to produce m16 rifles for 
the us department of defense 
with no buyer in sight the striking workers won a major victory 
in september 1989 when an nlrb administrative law judge ruled the 
strike was caused by colts unfair labor practices the judge 
ordered the company to reinstate the workers and pay them lost 
wages estimated as high as 40 million 
in november cf holding announced it had agreed to buy the 
firearms division there was no mention at the time of union or 
state participation although both were expected to be part of a 
final agreement 
borges said thursday his office had fully investigated the 
firearms division and the firearms industry and concluded the 
business was a good investment for the state 
borges said he knew of no other instance in which labor 
management and public and private investors joined to preserve a 
company as big as colts firearms division 
he described the deal as a bold exciting and very inventive 
partnership in the best tradition of samuel colts entrepreneurial 
spirit 
colt was founded in 1836 in hartford by samuel colt inventor of 
the first successful repeating pistol after colts death in 1862 
the company developed the sixshooter that almost every cowboy 
carried the legendary gun that won the west 
in addition to the m16 the standard armyissue rifle colt 
makes the colt 45 handgun the king cobra magnum revolver and the 
ar15 rifle 
