<TEXT>
three former northwest airlines pilots were 
charged by federal and state officials thursday with operating a 
boeing 727 commercial jetliner while under the influence of alcohol 
charges were filed separately by the us attorneys office in 
minneapolis and by north dakota officials against capt norman 
prouse 51 of conyers ga first officer robert kirchner 35 of 
highland ranch colo and second officer joseph balzer 34 of 
antioch tenn 
we consider the driving of a common carrier whether it be an 
aircraft a train or a bus while under the influence of alcohol to 
be a very serious offense us attorney jerry arnold told a news 
conference here 
according to an fbi agents affidavit prouse purchased 14 rum 
and diet cokes at a bar over a sixhour period the evening before 
the march 8 flight left fargo nd for minneapolis and another 
bar patron purchased five additional drinks for him the affidavit 
said the other two crew members were served seven pitchers of beer 
witnesses said prouse balzer and kirchner were visibly 
intoxicated at the bar the affidavit said between 7 to 8 hours 
expired from the time the pilots left the bar and their 630 am 
flight time 
tests conducted at the hennepin county medical center in 
minneapolis shortly after the pilots arrest showed prouse had a 
bloodalcohol level of 012 percent 
balzers bloodalcohol level was 007 percent and while 
kirchners was 006 percent according to the test results which 
were made available to the associated press 
federal regulations prohibit pilots from flying if they have 
higher than a 004 percent level the legal limit for driving a 
vehicle is 010 in most states 
arnold said the federal felony charges were brought under a 
statute passed by congress as part of the 1986 antidrug abuse act 
prohibiting operation of a common carrier while under the influence 
of alcohol or drugs 
the maximum penalty on the federal charges is 15 years in prison 
andor a 250000 fine he said 
arnold said arrangements were being made for the three pilots to 
turn themselves in voluntarily next week in minneapolis they are 
scheduled to be arraigned march 29 he said 
in north dakota the three were charged in cass county court 
with operating an aircraft while intoxicated and acting as an 
aircraft crew member within eight hours of drinking the charges 
each are misdemeanors punishable by a 1000 fine and one year in 
prison under north dakota law 
this kind of conduct by airline pilots should not be condoned 
and cannot be tolerated by todays traveling public county 
prosecutor robert hoy said its incumbent upon those individuals 
with positions of responsibility over this type of conduct to make 
sure it does not happen again 
prouse balzer and kirchner were detained in minneapolis upon 
landing flight 650 safely following a tip to federal authorities 
that the crew had been drinking the night before 
the airline has fired the three and the federal aviation 
administration has revoked their pilot licenses the three plan to 
appeal their license revocations their attorneys have said 
mark mcdermott a washington dc lawyer representing 
kirchner said the defense will do whatever we have to do to 
defend his rights 
bruce hanley the minneapolis attorney who represents balzer 
said his client will plead innocent he said it was too early to 
comment on the allegations in the governments affidavit 
prouse has an unlisted telephone number 
prosecutors from the city attorneys office in minneapolis have 
met with federal attorneys to discuss the case deputy city 
attorney mitchell rothman said wednesday his office would wait 
until federal authorities decided whether to prosecute the pilots 
before deciding whether to file city charges 
rothman had said the city isnt likely to prosecute if federal 
authorities do so 
bob gibbons northwest airlines director of media relations 
declined to comment thursday on the charges saying we wont 
have any viewpoint on any of the court action involving the former 
pilots 
